    <title>Simple Harmonic Motion</title>

    <introduction>
    	<p>
    		Simple harmonic motion is a special type of periodic motion in which displacement <m> x</m> from a reference point is a sine or cosine function of time.
    		<me>
    			x (t) = A\, \cos\,(2\pi f\,t) + B\, \cos\,(2\pi f\,t),
    		</me>
    		where <m> f </m> is frequency of the periodic motion, and <m>A</m> and <m> B</m> are constants. 
    	</p>
    	<p>
    		The motion of a block attached to a spring is the standard example of the simple harmonic motion. Other less familiar examples are a pendulum of small amplitude and small oscillations of buildings and other structures.
    	</p>
    </introduction>

